This subtree is the pure, side-effect-free translation layer between a resolved sandbox configuration and the actual `bwrap` command line — it produces a `Vec<OsString>` argv and nothing else. Depending on it gets you a single entry point, `build_bwrap_args(&BwrapConfig) -> Vec<OsString>`, plus the `BwrapConfig` type and the fixed in-cage path constants; no filesystem or subprocess work happens here, that's the caller's job elsewhere in the crate.

The coupling to watch: `config.rs` defines the in-cage path constants (`CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, `CAGE_RUN_DIR`, `API_SOCK_NAME`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_*`) and `build.rs` consumes them to emit bind-mount args at those exact paths — any other code in the crate that writes synthesized config files or expects specific in-cage paths must reference these same constants, since drift here fails silently inside the sandbox rather than at compile time. `mod.rs`'s doc comment is the authoritative spec for the whole mount layout (target RW at real host path per ADR-046, secret masking via empty-file RO binds, toolchain RO at identical paths, `/cage/bin` tmpfs, `/opt/cage/rules.md` RO, `/run/ctx` RO as the sole network egress via the API proxy socket) — `build.rs` must stay in sync with it on any change. `discover.rs` is a separate, non-pure concern (it does walk the filesystem) that feeds crate `src`/`tests` paths into the same tmpfs-overlay configuration story, but doesn't touch `BwrapConfig`/`build_bwrap_args` directly.

Subtree-spanning invariants: every bind target that the build side wires up traces to a constant in `config.rs`, never a hardcoded string; `mask_file` must be an empty regular file (not `/dev/null`, per bwrap's `nodev` bind behavior) or masked-secret reads fail with EACCES; and the cage always has `--unshare-net` + `--clearenv`, so `config.rs`'s `env` field is the complete cage environment and `/run/ctx`'s socket is the only egress path.

`config.rs` is the data/contract layer, `build.rs` is the argv-construction logic, `discover.rs` is a filesystem-walking helper for tmpfs overlay input, and `mod.rs` is the public surface plus the spec doc comment binding the other two together.